{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}

The '''Australian Nationalist Party (ANP)''' was a minor [[Australia|Australian]] [[List of political parties in Australia|political party]] that contested the [[Australian federal election, 1958|1958 federal election]]. The ANP unsuccessfully ran five candidates in [[Queensland]]: Noel Condie in the [[division of Bowman]], John Morgan in the [[division of Brisbane]], Mervyn Goldstiver in the [[division of Lilley]], Horace Burge in the [[division of Petrie]], and Ronald Edmonds in the [[division of Ryan]]. The party's objectives included opposition to [[communism]] and socialization, reducing taxes, restoring the proportion of [[England|British]] [[Immigration to Australia|immigration]] to 75% of the total, deportation of migrants convicted of certain crimes, increasing [[social services]], restoration of [[full employment]], opposition to salary rises for politicians, and support for states' rights.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jaensch|first=Dean|authorlink=Dean Jaensch|last2=Mathieson|first2=David|date=1998|title=A Plague on Both Your Houses: Minor Parties in Australia|publisher=[[Allen & Unwin]]|page=143|isbn=1-86448-421-7}}</ref>

