The use of '''fetal tissue in vaccines''' began in the 1930s.<ref name=cnn/> One of the first medical applications of [[fetus|fetal tissues]] was their use in the production of the first [[polio vaccine]]s.<ref name=cnn/> For example, in the 1950s, scientists at the [[Karolinska Institute]] in [[Sweden]] propagated a [[polio virus]] in fetal cells to make into a polio vaccine. The resulting [[vaccine]] was given to about 2,000 children.<ref name=science>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/01/fact-checking-congress-s-fetal-tissue-report |title=Fact-checking Congress’s fetal tissue report |last=Wadman |first=Meredith |date=2017-01-05 |website=Science |language=en |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> Such tissues are no longer used in polio vaccine development.<ref name=cnn/> Many other vaccines, including those for [[chicken pox vaccine|chicken pox]] and [[rubella vaccine|rubella]], are made using fetal tissue from two pregnancies terminated in the early 1960s.<ref name=cnn>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/07/17/health/fetal-tissue-explainer/index.html |title=How exactly fetal tissue is used for medicine |last=Storrs |first=Carina |date=2015-07-17 |website=CNN |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref><ref name="nejm">{{Cite journal |last=Charo |first=R. Alta |title=Fetal Tissue Fallout |url=http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMp1510279 |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=373 |issue=10 |pages=890–891 |doi=10.1056/nejmp1510279}}</ref> The same [[fibroblast]] cells from these pregnancies that were originally used to grow vaccine viruses have been growing in labs ever since, as the [[WI-38]] and [[MRC-5]] [[cell lines]]. They are still used to grow vaccine viruses today.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chop.edu/centers-programs/vaccine-education-center/vaccine-ingredients/fetal-tissues |title=Vaccine Ingredients – Fetal Tissues |last=Philadelphia |first=The Children's Hospital of |date=2014-11-06 |website=www.chop.edu |language=en |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.historyofvaccines.org/content/articles/human-cell-strains-vaccine-development |title=Human Cell Strains in Vaccine Development |website=History of Vaccines |language=en |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> As of March 2017, at least 300 million vaccines have been given that were made using the WI-38 line alone.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/future_tense/2017/03/the_woman_whose_aborted_fetus_helped_create_the_rubella_vaccine.html |title=Henrietta Lacks Wasn’t the Only Woman Who Unknowingly Contributed to Medical History |last=Wadman |first=Meredith |date=2017-03-02 |website=Slate |language=en-US |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>
==Vaccines== Vaccines that have been or are made using fetal tissue for the propagation of viruses include: *[[Adenovirus vaccine|Adenovirus]]<ref name=nature>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nature.com/news/medical-research-cell-division-1.13273 |title=Medical research: Cell division |last=Wadman |first=Meredith |date=2013-06-27 |website=Nature |pages=422–426 |language=en |doi=10.1038/498422a |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> *Chicken pox<ref name=science/> *[[Ebola vaccine|Ebola]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/medical-researchers-say-fetal-tissue-remains-essential |title=Scientists say fetal tissue remains essential for vaccines and developing treatments |last=Binkley |first=Collin |date=2015-08-11 |website=PBS NewsHour |language=en-US |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> *Polio<ref name=nature/> *[[Rabies vaccine|Rabies]]<ref name=nature/> *Rubella<ref name=science/> *[[Shingles vaccine|Shingles]]<ref name=nature/> Of these, the vaccines approved for use in the United States include some of those against rabies ([[Imovax]]), rubella, chicken pox, shingles, and adenovirus (as of January 2017).<ref name=science/> ==Ethical issues== Despite [[Holy See|the Vatican]]'s longstanding and complete opposition to [[abortion]], their [[Pontifical Academy for Life]] concluded in 2005 that parents should allow their children to receive vaccines made from fetal tissue, to protect them from [[infectious disease]]s. The Academy also called for the development of new vaccines that can be made by other means.<ref name="nejm"/> Similarly, the [[National Catholic Bioethics Center]] states on its website that "...one is morally free to use the vaccine regardless of its historical association with abortion. The reason is that the risk to public health, if one chooses not to vaccinate, outweighs the legitimate concern about the origins of the vaccine..."<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/aborted-fetuses-vaccines/story?id=29005539 |title=What Aborted Fetuses Have to Do With Vaccines |last=News |first=A. B. C. |date=2015-02-17 |website=ABC News |language=en |access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> ==Legal issues== [[Leonard Hayflick]], the scientist who created the WI-38 cell line, provoked a legal battle with the [[National Institutes of Health]] when he took stocks of them from his lab and shipped them to people for money.<ref name="nature"/> ==References== {{Reflist}} {{Vaccines}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Fetal tissue in vaccines}}
