'''Medicines reconciliation''' is the process of ensuring that a hospital patient's [[medication]] list is as up-to-date as possible. It is usually undertaken by a [[pharmacist]], and may include consulting several sources such as the patient, their relatives or carers, or their [[primary care physician]]. In the [[United Kingdom]], guidelines on medicines reconciliation are provided by the [[National Institute for Health and Care Excellence]] (NICE) in collaboration with the [[National Patient Safety Agency]].<ref name="NICE NPSA">National Patient Safety Agency. NICE NPSA medicines reconciliation adults in hospital. Patient Safety Alert, Reference number 1035. Issue date 1 December 2007. London, UK. [http://www.npsa.nhs.uk/corporate/news/guidance-to-improve-medicines-reconciliation/]</ref> In accordance with these, it should be carried out within 24 hours of admission to hospital.

==Importance==

Research has shown that, on average, there is around a 20% discrepancy between medications prescribed on admission to hospital and the true medication list for a given patient.<ref name="Urban">Urban R, Armitage G, Morgan J, et-al. Custom and practice: a multi-center study of medicines reconciliation following admission in four acute hospitals in the UK. ''Res Social Adm Pharm''. 2014; 10: 355-68. {{PMID|24529643}}</ref> Chronic medications are stopped in about 11% of the patients after elective [[Surgery|surgeries]]<ref name="Bell1">Bell CM, Bajcar J, Bierman AS, Li P, Mamdani MM, Urbach DR. Potentially unintended discontinuation of long-term medication use after elective surgical procedures. ''Arch Intern Med''. 2006; 166: 2525-31. {{PMID|17159020}}</ref> and 33% of the patients after admission to [[intensive care unit]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bell|first=Chaim M.|last2=Rahimi-Darabad|first2=Parisa|last3=Orner|first3=Avi I.|date=2006-09-01|title=Discontinuity of chronic medications in patients discharged from the intensive care unit|journal=Journal of General Internal Medicine|volume=21|issue=9|pages=937–941|doi=10.1111/j.1525-1497.2006.00499.x|issn=1525-1497|pmc=1831608|pmid=16918738}}</ref> The most common omissions are [[inhalers]] and [[analgesia]]. There are also a small minority of errors in prescribing drugs such as [[insulin]] or [[warfarin]], which could have catastrophic consequences including death of the patient. [[Pharmacist]] involvement help reasons for drug discontinuation being documented<ref name="Yeung2">Yeung E. Are we legitimately stopping medications? Use of pharmacist and junior doctor teaching to improve medication reconciliation. Br J Gen Pract. November 11, 2016. London, UK. [http://bjgp.org/content/are-we-legitimately-stopping-medications-use-pharmacist-and-junior-doctor-teaching-improve]</ref> and [[adverse drug reaction]]s being reconciled in the prescription charts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yeung|first=Eugene Y. H.|date=2015-10-01|title=Adverse drug reactions: a potential role for pharmacists|journal=The British Journal of General Practice: The Journal of the Royal College of General Practitioners|volume=65|issue=639|pages=511|doi=10.3399/bjgp15X686821|issn=1478-5242|pmc=4582849|pmid=26412813}}</ref> The value of medicines reconciliation is in noticing and correcting these errors before they have a chance to adversely affect the patient concerned.

